  "A discount applied to a bundled policy": "",
  "A person who is covered under another person's insurance policy": "",
  "The person who delivers insurance documents": "",
  "A rider (or endorsement) adds or modifies coverage beyond the standard policy. Common examples include jewelry riders, home office riders, or identity theft protection endorsements.": "",
  "What does 'elimination period' mean in disability insurance?": "",
  "The maximum duration of benefit payments": "",
  "The waiting period after becoming disabled before benefit payments begin, typically 30, 60, or 90 days": "",
  "The time required to cancel a disability policy": "",
  "The period during which the insurance company reviews your claim": "",
  "The elimination period is the waiting period between the onset of disability and when benefits start. A longer elimination period (90 days vs. 30 days) reduces premiums but requires more savings to bridge the gap.": "",
  "What does 'Health Savings Account' (HSA) mean?": "",
  "A tax-advantaged account available to HDHP enrollees that allows pre-tax contributions, tax-free growth, and tax-free withdrawals for qualified medical expenses": "",
  "A savings account offered by hospitals to pay for medical bills": "",
  "A flexible spending account that must be used within the year": "",
  "A government-provided health insurance plan": "",
  "An HSA combines three tax benefits (deductible contributions, tax-free growth, tax-free medical withdrawals) with no use-it-or-lose-it deadline. After age 65, funds can be used for any purpose (taxed like a Traditional IRA if non-medical).": "",
  "What does 'policy exclusion' mean?": "",
  "The process of removing a person from a policy": "",
  "A special provision that enhances coverage": "",
  "A type of insurance that excludes certain people from coverage": "",
  "Specific events, conditions, or circumstances listed in the policy that are not covered by the insurance": "",
  "Policy exclusions define what is NOT covered. Common exclusions include floods and earthquakes in homeowner's policies, and pre-existing conditions in some health policies. Reading exclusions is essential to avoid claim denials.": "",
